Elisabeth Linek

Lab Exercise: Explore Football Data

This dataset containts soccer (or as Europeans prefer: football) player skill ratings (at the time of September 2011). The skill ratings are from the PES Stats Database (PSD), a community-based approach to create a database with accurate statistics and skill ratings for soccer players (originally for the video game “Pro Evolution Soccer” by Konami).

It contains no less than 43 variables on 1851 players from 4 European Leagues (Bundesliga, La Liga, Premier League, Serie A).

Tasks

  1. Visually explore the offensive (Attack) and defensive (Defence) skills of soccer players.

    But before going straight to the code, take a few minutes, think and take notes:
    1. What a priori expectations about the data and possible patterns do you have?
    2. What general exploration strategy would be appropriate?
    3. Which comparisons are possible and interesting?
    4. Which graphical formats would be useful to make these comparisons?
  2. Make sure you experiment with
    1. at least three graphical formats as well as
    2. with comparisons within a single plot and comparisons across multiple plots!

    If you are new to R, have a look at the following two videos on the course site: “surv752-code-05-Adding_Elements_to_an_Exisiting_Plot” “surv752-code-06-Arranging_Multiple_Plots”

  3. Finally, try to construct a “bullet graph” as invented by Stephen Few as well as a “slope graph” and “sparklines” as invented by Edward Tufte. (For these latter two graphical formats it’s best to use data with a time component - so you may want to go back to the freedom house data.) For this exercise you my find the lines(), segments() and rect() plotting functions helpful. ___________________________________________

1. visual exploration

helpful wrt. positions https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_football_positions

  1. What a priori expectations about the data and possible patterns do you have?
    • Forwards (offencive players) will have likely better offensive skills and defenders defensive players will have rather better defensive skills. Midfeilders will be likely in between depending on their position forward/defence the according skill will be higher (i.e. defensive midfielders (DMF) will have a higher defence skillset whereas offensive (AMF) will have a likely better offensive skillset).
    • Midfielders should have a higher passing accuracy than forwards.
    • Left footed players will play more likeley on the left side in case they don’t play on both sides.
    • The four represented countries in the dataset represent the top four ranked countries in the UEFA association ranking by country of the season 2010-11. The order of the ranking was England, Spain, Italy and Germany at which England was ranked first (not the season ranking!). This could be reflected in the dataset. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010%E2%80%9311_UEFA_Champions_League https://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/uefarankings/country/season=2010/index.html
  2. What general exploration strategy would be appropriate?
    • use the summary function
    • dplyr to group and and filter the data
  3. Which comparisons are possible and interesting?
    • Top n teams of the country vs the rest.
    • Player position distribution wrt. total number of players.
    • Avg. height by country
    • dribbling vs passing
    • Nationalities playing soccer in the four countries ->foreign vs. local
    • Attack/Defence wrt. age
  4. Which graphical formats would be useful to make these comparisons?
    • since it’s just Attack and Defence to compare it’s maybe best to go with small minimals to get a wider scope

ad_by_age <- football_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(Age)) %>%
  group_by(Age, Position) %>%
  summarise(meanA = mean(Attack), meanD = mean(Defence), n = n()) %>%
  arrange(Age, meanA, meanD)

max_age <- ad_by_age$Age %>% max

min_ma <- ad_by_age$meanA %>% min
max_ma <- ad_by_age$meanA %>% max

leagues <- c('Bundesliga', 'LaLiga', 'PremierLeague', 'SerieA')
nationality <- list('German', 'Spanish', list('English', 'Welsh'), 'Italian')
positions <- c("GK", "D", "M", "F")

national_player <- function(i) {
  return (football_data %>%
    filter(League == leagues[i], Nationality %in% nationality[[i]]) %>%
    group_by(Position) %>%
    summarise(meanA = mean(Attack), meanD = mean(Defence), n = n()) %>%
    arrange(meanA, meanD))
}

foreign_player <- function(i) {
  return (football_data %>%
    filter(League == leagues[i], !Nationality %in% nationality[[i]]) %>%
    group_by(Position) %>%
    summarise(meanA = mean(Attack), meanD = mean(Defence), n = n()) %>%
    arrange(meanA, meanD))
}

par(mfrow=c(2, 4))
for (i in 1:4)  {
  natp <- national_player(i)
  natp$Position <- factor(natp$Position, levels(natp$Position)[c(3, 1, 4, 2)])
  print(natp)
  forp <- foreign_player(i)
  forp$Position <- factor(forp$Position, levels(forp$Position)[c(3, 1, 4, 2)])
  plot(0, 0, xlim=c(1,4), ylim=c(20, 100), xaxt="n", main=leagues[i], xlab="Position", ylab="Attack")
  axis(1, at=1:4, labels=positions)
  points(natp$Position, natp$meanA, type="p", pch=20, col="red")
  points(forp$Position, forp$meanA, type="p", pch=20, col="blue")
}

sparklines <- function(d, i) {
  plot(d[,i], lwd=0.5, axes=F, ylab="", xlab="", main="", type="l", new=F)
  axis(4, at=d[nrow(d),i], labels=d[nrow(d),i], tick=F, las=1, line=-1.5,
       family="serif", cex.axis=1.2)
  axis(4, at=d[nrow(d),i], labels=names(d[i]), tick=F, line=1.5,
       family="serif", cex.axis=1.4, las=1)
  text(which.max(d[,i]), max(d[,i]), labels=max(d[,i]),
       family="serif", cex=1.2, adj=c(0.5,3))
  text(which.min(d[,i]), min(d[,i]), labels=min(d[,i]),
       family="serif", cex=1.2, adj=c(0.5,-2.5))
  ymin <- min(d[,i])
  tmin <- which.min(d[,i])
  ymax<-max(d[,i])
  tmax<-which.max(d[,i])
  points(x=c(tmin,tmax), y=c(ymin,ymax), pch=19, col=c("red","blue"), cex=1)
  rect(0, summary(d[,i])[2], nrow(d), summary(d[,i])[4], border=0,
       col = rgb(190, 190, 190, alpha=90, maxColorValue=255))
}
sparklines(beaver1, 3)
sparklines(beaver2, 3)

library(ggplot2)

bullet.graph <- function(bg.data){

  # compute max and half for the ticks and labels
  max.bg <- max(bg.data$high)
  mid.bg <- max.bg / 2

  gg <- ggplot(bg.data)
  gg <- gg + geom_bar(aes(measure, high),  fill="goldenrod2", stat="identity", width=0.5, alpha=0.2)
  gg <- gg + geom_bar(aes(measure, mean),  fill="goldenrod3", stat="identity", width=0.5, alpha=0.2)
  gg <- gg + geom_bar(aes(measure, low),   fill="goldenrod4", stat="identity", width=0.5, alpha=0.2)
  gg <- gg + geom_bar(aes(measure, value), fill="black",  stat="identity", width=0.2)
  gg <- gg + geom_errorbar(aes(y=target, x=measure, ymin=target, ymax=target), color="red", width=0.45)
  gg <- gg + geom_point(aes(measure, target), colour="red", size=5)
  gg <- gg + scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0,max.bg,mid.bg))
  gg <- gg + coord_flip()
  gg <- gg + theme(axis.text.x=element_text(size=17),
                   axis.title.x=element_blank(),
                   axis.line.y=element_blank(),
                   axis.text.y=element_text(hjust=1, color="black"),
                   axis.ticks.y=element_blank(),
                   axis.title.y=element_blank(),
                   legend.position="none",
                   panel.background=element_blank(),
                   panel.border=element_blank(),
                   panel.grid.major=element_blank(),
                   panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),
                   plot.background=element_blank())

  return(gg)
}
